Understanding Container Networking

By default, containers are isolated

	• Each container has its own network namespace
	• Containers can't communicate with each other automatically
	• Container can't be accessed from outside without configuration

What we need:

	• Containers to access the internet (for updates, APIs)
	• Container to communicate with each other (web app -> databse)
	• External access to container (user accessing your web app)

Docker Provides:

	• Built in networking solutions to handle all of this

Default Bridge Network 

How it works

Every container gets:

	• Automatically connect to default bridge.
	• Its own IP address (typically 172.17.0.x range)
	• Access to internet through host
	• Needs -p flag for external access

Example:

docker run -d --name web nginx
docker run -d --name db mysql

# Both on default bridge
# Can communicate via IP, but Not by name
# No external access unless ports mapped

Limitation : No automatic DNS - must use IP address


Custom Bridge Networks

Create a custom network:

docker network create <network_name>

Run container on this network:

docker run -d --name db --network <network_name> mysql
docker run -d --name web --network <network_name> nginx

# Now containers can communicate by name!
# Web container can reach db at hostname "db"

Key advantage:

Automatic DNS resolution by container name

Example :

Web app connects to database at mysql://db:3306


Host Network Mode - Direct Host Access

Syntax:

docker run -d --network host nginx

Behaviour:

Container uses host's network directly
No network isolation
Container ports=host ports (no -p needed)
Highest network performance

Use cases:

Performance-critical applications
Network monitoring tools
When you need access to host network interfaces. 

Limitation : Only works on Linux hosts, port conflicts possible

